# A [[facetious]] or [[insult]]ing remark, a [[jeer]] or [[taunt]].
#* c. '''1600''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|Hamlet}}'', Act V, Scene 1,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=hamlet&Scope=entire&pleasewait=1&msg=pl]</sup>
#*: Where be your '''gibes''' now? your [[gambol]]s? your songs? your flashes of merriment that were wont to set the table on a roar? Not one now, to mock your own grinning?
#* '''1746''', {{w|Charles Macklin}}, ''King Henry the VII: Or the Popish Impostor. A Tragedy'', London: R. Francklin et al., Act II, p. 24,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004784727.0001.000]</sup>
#*: {{...}} Come, come, we
#*: All are Friends, nor have we Time for '''Jibe''',
#*: Or Anger now, but 'gainst our common Foes,
#*: The ''French'' and ''Scot''; there let your Pray’rs, and Jests,
#*: And Blows, be levell’d.
#* '''1862''', {{w|Christina Rossetti}}, “{{w|Goblin Market}}” in ''{{w|Goblin Market and Other Poems}}'', London: Macmillan, pp. 24-25,<sup>[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100613555]</sup>
#*: She ran and ran
#*: As if she feared some goblin man
#*: Dogged her with '''gibe''' or curse
#*: Or something worse:
#* '''1903''', {{w|W. E. B. Du Bois}}, ''{{w|The Souls of Black Folk}}'', Chapter 12,<sup>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/408/408-h/408-h.htm]</sup>
#*: He bent to all the '''gibes''' and prejudices, to all hatred and discrimination, with that rare courtesy which is the armor of pure souls.
#* '''1920''', {{w|F. Scott Fitzgerald}}, ''{{w|This Side of Paradise}}'', Book One, Chapter 1,<sup>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/805/805-h/805-h.htm]</sup>
#*: He had written two novels: one of them violently anti-Catholic, just before his conversion, and five years later another, in which he had attempted to turn all his clever '''jibes''' against Catholics into even cleverer innuendoes against Episcopalians.
#: ''He flung subtle '''jibes''' at her until she couldn't bear to work with him any longer.''

